Horrible experience and pathetic food. The least you expect from a restaurant is ambiance and basic authentic cuisine. We went as a group of six people (all Indian) and ordered very regular food like daal, roti, paneer and chicken. In the name of chilli paneer we were served paneer dipped in "vinegar" tomato curry - I bet if any paneer dish in India is cooked in vinegar. Then came tandoori chicken which was without any spices and guess what -- it was fried. A restaurant that mess-up as basic as tandoori chicken has a special place in hell. Raita was too sour/fermented as if yoghurt used was from paleolithic era. Ambiance was shady and reeked of negativity. The manager was constantly yelling on serving staff (felt really bad for those minimum wage employee) as during our dinner alone 3 parties complained about the quality of food but he thought it was mistake of servers. Being an Indian I will never recommend anyone to eat here ever.

Used to go here all the time when I lived in Central. The staff are friendly and the food is great. I usually did dinner, but the lunch buffet is great too. Having tried a lot of Indian restaurants in the area, I can say that this place is definitely one of the best. Reminds me of being back home. I loved the Gobi kaju masala. There’s plenty of great vegetarian options. Highly recommend checking out this place.

Last evening we were more than completely satisfied with the quality of food and most importantly the blended flavorful spices and level of heat were perfect. Here are the dishes we ordered for take-out and every plate was amazing. Vegetable samosa - these are plump, crispy samosas with nicely seasoned potatoes and vegetables Tandoori mixed platter - the chicken was cooked to perfection, moist and mild. Mild and medium chicken Biryani - delicious! Spicy Lamb Jalfrazee was superb, tender and spicy the way we enjoy it. Spicy Chicken Korma - wow! So delicious ! Dahi Papri Chaat! - Amazing dish. I think I could eat it all day. Spicy tamarind chutney and raita. Holy smokes soooooo delicious! Mixed naan basket - the best for “mopping” up the sauces. This wonderful restaurant knows what they are doing and is absolutely perfect. I could eat this meal everyday. I am already planning what I will be ordering next time to try. I am certain which ever dish we choose will be delightful.

So this story starts off from ordering a plain dosa awhile ago and it was a bit burnt so we told them for next time please make sure it’s not burnt. Today we order a plain dosa again and we remind them to not burn it like last time. What happens instead? They give us an extremely raw dosa like it was barely on the stove and was just taken off midway and given to us. The dosa felt like raw dough and was as white as dough. It seems like whoever took our order was spiting us for reminding them of their mistake of burning the dosa. Not okay, never coming back here.

Extremely disappointed.  I have been a loyal customer of India Pavilion for over 20 years.  During that time I have ordered from them countless times as they are 700 feet from my house.  I have always thought that their food and service were good.  Yesterday I convinced my husband to forego ordering from grub hub to support our neighborhood restaurant.  He walked to pick up the order and brought it back.  After we had started eating we realized they did not include the naan.  He called the restaurant and asked if they would bring it to us.  It is less than a five minute walk.  We were already seated for dinner.  They were not busy.  They said no.  In this time, when restaurants are struggling and take-out is their lifeline, they have to get it right and they have to make it right when the mess up.  They finally agreed to bring the naan, but never showed up.  I will never do business with them again.  20 years of take out dinners and using them to cater big dinners, and they wouldn't send someone 700 feet to correct their own mistake.

Toward the end of lunch, I briefly step away from the table, just to get back to the table a few minutes later, but to see that the waiters removed the plate that had some food in it. I tell them that I had not left. They apologize for misunderstanding and for removing the food. I say, ‘no problem’, and leave. A couple of weeks later, the manager approaches me to show a picture on his phone of a plate with food, accusing me of not finishing the food I had on my plate during my last visit!!! This is a real incident, not a joke! (Occurred, February 17, around 2:45 pm). Now, you might think “no restaurant in America could be full of such hostility against customers!” But don’t worry. I’m sure most customers are not  harassed with such disrespectful treatment. So, enjoy the food. Just know that by supporting this establishment, this is the outstanding level of professionalism and  customer service that you would be feeding!

This is a go to spot for meeting up with friends for a great dinner. We order lots of dishes to share. The rice is fluffy and aromatic, the chicken lentil soup is a little spicy if you like heat, if not get the coconut soup for a treat. The chicken Tikka masala is creamy and comforting and medium is about good for spice level unless you really love spicy food. The chicken biryani was tender, fragrant, and full of veggies, cashews, and golden raisins. We opted for two kinds of naan- garlic and peshwari both were soft and flavorful. The service was a little lackluster but we weren't rushed. If we asked for something, we got it, but we weren't really checked on. Definitely worth stopping in if you like authentic comforting Indian food.

I think I am being generous here. Firstly, there are no curtains or blinds, and thus place feels like a greenhouse. Secondly, when we asked for a change to a different table, they looked around a completely empty restaurant and said "I don't think there are any available". Finally we were shifted to a different table, but our troubles ensued. Now I felt like I was in the middle of a freezer chamber. What a great place to eat some great good. It was such a great atmosphere, it was like being in India with the decor and the music playing in the background. The buffet we had was excellent, all the food was piping hot and delishous. The window to the cooks in the kitchen was a nice added touch, seeing the cooks make the food was nice. I wish I waited to Take a picture of the food, the aroma was so enticing I couldn’t help myself.  First and formost the simplicity of their vegetables samosa is out of this world, the flaky buttery crust And several spices in the mix is by far superior than any other samosa I had period.  Came here with a friend and ordered 3 orders of samosa, the chicken and kebab platter rice and mango lassis,  The flavor in the chicken tandoori is fantastic, which goes perfect  with the complementary mint sauce and naan bread.  Chicken so juicy, I can’t tell my mom about this place , cuz she’ll kill me.  Nonetheless the owner is wonderful and attentive  Great waiters and waitresses, gave awesome service.  This place is so great, if you want authentic flavorful Indian cuisine, from top to bottom,  Indian pavilion is a must.

India Pavilion enjoys the distinction of being the oldest Indian restaurant in Cambridge. Recently renovated, the interior is modern and appealing. The actual quality of the food leaves much to be desired. I rarely observe subcontinent patrons, which speaks volumes. Parking is challenging, as always, for Cambridge, but the restaurant is a one-minute walk from the MBTA Central Square subway station.
